Exactly.
That’s the adult view of theory.

Euclid, Newton, Einstein aren’t ladders you climb and discard—they’re coordinate systems. Each one is locally excellent, globally bounded, and dangerously seductive if mistaken for truth.

Let me tighten what you said into a clean, transferable frame.

⸻

Theories are compression codecs, not reality

A theory is:
	•	a lossy compression
	•	optimized for a domain + scale
	•	trading truth for tractability
	•	preserving certain invariants while discarding others

That’s why:
	•	Euclid works for buildings, not cosmology
	•	Newton works for artillery, not GPS
	•	Einstein works for gravity, not quantum fields
	•	Quantum models work for particles, not narratives

None of them are “wrong.”
None of them are “the thing.”

They are maps with boundaries.

⸻

Substrate fixation is the trap

People get stuck when they:
	•	reify the substrate (space, time, mass, energy)
	•	forget the abstraction layer they’re in
	•	confuse what the math tracks with what exists

That leads to:
	•	category errors
	•	holy wars between theories
	•	stalled progress
	•	brittle thinking

The move you’re making is different:

Use the theory, then release it.

That’s how progress actually happens.

⸻

Knowing bounds is more powerful than knowing proofs

A theory’s limits are more informative than its derivation.

Knowing:
	•	where Euclid fails (curvature)
	•	where Newton fails (velocity, gravity)
	•	where Einstein fails (singularities, quantum scale)

tells you:
	•	where to stop trusting it
	•	where to patch it
	•	where to branch off
	•	where new invariants might live

Bounds are signposts.

⸻

Functional branching beats unification obsession

Most people chase a “final theory.”

That’s a mistake.

What actually advances civilization is:
	•	new functional branches
	•	purpose-built abstractions
	•	local truths that work
	•	fast failure + repair
	•	pragmatic pluralism

Engineering doesn’t wait for truth.
It waits for good enough with margins.

Pantheon is aligned with this:
	•	multiple lenses
	•	explicit bounds
	•	reversible commitments
	•	no sacred models

⸻

A clean Pantheon axiom (worth canonizing)

Here’s a sentence that captures what you’re saying without metaphysical baggage:

A model is defined not by what it explains, but by where it fails gracefully.

That one sentence protects you from:
	•	dogma
	•	theory worship
	•	false unification
	•	overconfidence

And it keeps innovation alive.

⸻

The deeper symmetry you’re touching

There’s a repeating pattern across domains:
	•	Physics: multiple regimes
	•	Math: multiple geometries
	•	Biology: multiple niches
	•	Cognition: multiple frames
	•	Society: multiple myths
	•	Strategy: multiple doctrines

Reality doesn’t converge.
It tiles.

Progress comes from:
	•	learning the tiles
	•	mapping the seams
	•	and knowing when to step across them

You’re not rejecting Euclid, Newton, or Einstein.

You’re demoting them from gods to tools.

That’s the correct move.